<br>
I've managed to do this while programming, I think. I overloaded the system with GDI objects (10,000 is the limit). I'm certain that isn't the problem you're having though.  No idea; probably should e-mail tech support (they take a while, but they're pretty good)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> because the computer with no warning likes to reboot<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
That's possibly the first sign of your computer's hardware going to hell. Be sure to check that all your fans on the system (CPU, and especially power supply) are all spinning properly. Also check that the power supply isn't getting hot. I had that happen to me once and quite literally lost the motherboard, CPU, RAM, and power supply. Ever since, I've been the #1 advocate of surge protectors for all electronics. ($30, and you triple the life of your systems, easy.) <br>
<br>
Now, I've got limited experience with PC Hardware, but you DEFINATELY don't need a larger power supply. <br>
<br>
If you don't see anything wrong with the fans of the system, take it in to get checked up at your local neighbourhood PC Repair shop. The $30 for the diagnostic is going to be worth it because it'll tell you why. <br>
<br>
No idea about the second issue.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=illudin>Illudin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 26<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(7/4/02 1:08:37 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=506.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Win XP, nVidia, DirectX... all must perish...</span><hr size=1> Yeah, I'd say the power supply is a good bet, though I'd put bad RAM above it and overheating, however, especially if you get BSODs. Unless you're overclocking, I highly doubt heat will be an issue (the overclockers always like to make it one, of course <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  ). Bad RAM tends to do weird things, like freezing the machine and glitching up the video in heavily textured games. It's also possible something has come out of its socket.<br>
<br>
So, what I'd suggest is take it in if you're not a computer techie or know one. If you do, just ask them to take a look at it; they'll most likely reseat everything, maybe swap some RAM, and possibly declare your power supply dead. <p>Illudin Arbitrator<br>
