"Onward, all, to our destinies! Adventure awaits!"</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uwessleythewolf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Wessley The Wolf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The Wolf</span><br>  Posts: 107<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(7/4/02 2:59:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=506.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Win XP, nVidia, DirectX... all must perish...</span><hr size=1> Overheating will cause your computer to reboot itself if you've got an onboard thermometer. (It tries to cool itself down by turning itself off).<br>
<br>
As for the crash to the desktop thing...  Never ever download the drivers that WinXP update gives you for an NVidia card.  If you want to update your drivers, go to www.nvidia.com and download the reference drivers.<br>
<br>
I say never ever download the WinXP drivers from the update because they're really glitchy when it comes to NVidia cards and WinXP has a real problem giving up driver files.  So, say you download the drivers from the XP update...then realize you shouldn't have done that.  When you install the reference drivers from NVidia's site, WinXP sometimes will ignore the new drivers and use the old one.  Or use bits and pieces of the old one.  It's really annoying and the way to fix it is rather long and involved because XP was made to handle hardware and drivers as much as it can without user input.  So most of the time XP just ignores what you tell it anyway.<br>
<br>
Make sure the fan on your NVidia card is working (plugged up properly and spinning).  As Mylodi said, make sure everything is well seated (pushed in) and all your fans are working.<br>
<br>
Go to Start -&gt; Run  and type DxDiag  This will pop up program.  Click on each tab and run the tests to see if they all run properly.  (When you go to check the full screen mode you may have to do it twice because sometimes the GeForce4 takes a second to switch to full screen mode and the test doesn't really last that long).<br>
<br>
Now, here's what tech support will tell you:    Depending on your sound card, you may have your sound acceleration turned up too high or too low.  In DxDiag, click on the sound tab and if your sound acceleration is as far up as it will go turn it down a notch.  If it is down a notch turn it up one.  (Seriously, this is what tech support will tell you, I'm not making this up).<br>
<br>
They'll also tell you that you may have your graphics acceleration set too high (which I think is a bit of a joke) but I'm sure they wouldn't tell you that if it didn't work for some people.  So, right click on your desktop and choose Properties.  Click on the Settings Tab then choose Advanced.  Click on the Troubleshoot tab and if your graphics acceleration is set to the max turn it down a notch.<br>
<br>
...And that's about all I can tell you. = )  If none of that works, then turn it all back to the way it was.<br>
<br>
