 <p><a href="http://pub96.ezboard.com/bdreadgnomepirates"><img border="0" src="http://www.strike9.com/file.aspx/path=/maladominus/fullsize/malsig3.gif"></a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ucaillougna.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Caillou GNA</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 227<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(7/11/02 5:32:28 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=506.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Win XP, nVidia, DirectX... all must perish...</span><hr size=1> One last thing.... look at the drivers of the other things impacted by playing online:  sound card and network interface card.<br>
<br>
My boyfriend did a format &amp; reinstall, after installing EQ he would crash to the desktop after it reported packets dropping like flies.  I had another NIC, so he tried that to no avail.  He looked in the settings &amp; found all the PCI cards on the same IRQ.  Conflicts?  hmmm... He tried getting it to behave and let him put them on other IRQs but they wouldn't and were still an issue.  He then took out the sound card &amp; -bing- it worked, no packet loss, no crashing EQ.  Later, he found updated drivers for his sound card &amp; was even running with sound again... all with no crashing.<br>
<br>
Direct X was recently upgraded &amp; part of the upgrading of files when you start EQ is Direct X.  Direct X is -all- multimedia, video AND sound.  <br>
<br>
Update the drivers of all your various devices in your computer, preferably directly from the sites of the various manufacturers.<br>
<br>
-Caillou Kyrielle <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/usmallcutepuppy.showPublicProfile?language=EN>smallcutepuppy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 424<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(7/11/02 5:37:43 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=506.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Win XP, nVidia, DirectX... all must perish...</span><hr size=1> Athlons and GeForce cards both tend to run VERY hot. As others have said, check into the possibility of overheating. Take the case off your machine. Make sure the fans on your CPU and video card are working. Point a fan into the case if you have to. See if that helps.<br>
<br>
AMD boards (and possibly Athlon CPUs in particular) and GeForce cards are also somewhat notorious for being power hogs. If you have at least a 250W power supply you should be all right, but if not, you may indeed want to look into upgrading. You may want to get a new one anyway, if the computer is rebooting itself.<br>
<br>
Just passing along what my research has indicated, as I'm still in the process of piecing together my own dear departed Athlon 800 after losing the motherboard, CPU and power supply. It happened after about a week of the &quot;spontaneous rebooting&quot; phenomenon. My prime suspects are that either the CPU overheated (the fan was busted) or that the power supply shorted out or caused a surge or something (my hard drive was fried - still under warranty fortunately - and that power supply now instantly burns out any motherboard it's plugged into. Very ugly). Based on my experience, I'd recommend checking into both those possibilities so you can possibly avoid my fate. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :| --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/indifferent.gif ALT=":|"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uveloxiavoluptuous.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Veloxia Voluptuous</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Corrupted Halfling</span><br>  Posts: 856<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(7/11/02 10:37:04 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=506.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Win XP, nVidia, DirectX... all must perish...</span><hr size=1> also might want to install the driver given with the video card instead of windows XP generic. My Gforce 4 4200 128meg card barely runs with the generic driver, so i use the driver that came with the card even though it is &quot;not tested and approved by Windows XP&quot; which basically means that company isnt willing to send microsoft a 10k for the approving signature. <p><BR><B>Baroness Veloxia Voluptuous </B><BR>
